<hr>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>Examiner to ask questions from EITHER Frame 1 or Frame 2</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Frame 1 (Where you live now)</p>
<p dir="ltr">Let’s talk about where you live now</p>
<p dir="ltr">- Which town or city do you live in now?</p>
<p dir="ltr">- Are there any things you don’t like about your area? (What are they?)</p>
<p dir="ltr">- Do you think you will continue to live there for a long time? (Why? Why not?)</p>
<p dir="ltr">- What are some changes in the area recently?</p>
<p dir="ltr">- Do you live in a house or an apartment?</p>
<p dir="ltr">- What is your favourite room in your home? (Why?)</p>
<p dir="ltr">- What things make your home pleasant to live in? (Why?)</p>
<p dir="ltr">- Are the people in your neighbourhood nice and friendly?</p>
<p dir="ltr">- Do you know any of your neighbours?</p>
<p dir="ltr">- Is the place where you live quiet or noisy?</p>
<p dir="ltr">Frame 2 (Work/ Study)</p>
<p dir="ltr">Let’s talk about what you do. Do you work or are you a student?</p>
<p dir="ltr">(Work)</p>
<p dir="ltr">- What kind of work do you do?</p>
<p dir="ltr">- What do you find most interesting about your work? (Why?)</p>
<p dir="ltr">- Which is more important to you – the people you work with or the work you do? (Why?)</p>
<p dir="ltr">- Do you work best in the morning or the afternoon? (Why?)</p>
<p dir="ltr">- Would you like to change the place you work? (Why?)</p>
<p dir="ltr" style="padding-left: 40px;"><strong> </strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">(Study)</p>
<p dir="ltr">- What do you study?</p>
<p dir="ltr">- What do you find most interesting about your studies? (Why?)</p>
<p dir="ltr">- Which is more important to you—the teachers or the other students on your course? (Why?)</p>
<p dir="ltr">- How much time do you spend studying every week?</p>
<p dir="ltr">- How do you usually travel to the city where you study?</p>
<p dir="ltr">- Do you study best in the morning or the afternoon? (Why?)</p>
<p dir="ltr">- Have you always wanted to study this subject/ these subjects (Why/ Why not?)</p>
<hr>
<p><span style="font-size: 14pt; background-color: #fbeeb8;"><strong>1 Street market</strong></span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>1 What do people usually buy at the street market?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">People usually buy fresh produce like fruits, vegetables, and meat at street markets. You can also find local snacks, household items, and sometimes even clothes or accessories. Street markets are known for their affordable prices and the variety of goods available, which is why they’re popular with locals.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>2 Do you prefer to go shopping in the shopping mall or at the street market?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">I prefer the shopping mall for most things, as it’s more comfortable, especially in hot or rainy weather. However, for fresh food, I think the street market is better because the produce is usually fresher and sometimes even cheaper. Each has its advantages, so it really depends on what I’m looking for.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>3 When was the last time you went to a street market?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">The last time I went to a street market was about two weeks ago. I went with my family to buy some fresh vegetables and seafood for the weekend. It was a lively experience with lots of people and a variety of goods, which made the shopping trip more interesting.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>4 Are there many street markets in Vietnam?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Yes, there are plenty of street markets in Vietnam. They’re a big part of daily life, especially in cities like Hanoi and Ho Chi Minh City, as well as in smaller towns and rural areas. Vietnamese street markets offer a variety of goods, from fresh produce and seafood to clothes, household items, and local snacks. They’re popular because of their affordable prices and the lively atmosphere, and they’re also a great place to experience Vietnamese culture and try traditional foods.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="ltr"><span style="font-size: 14pt; background-color: #fbeeb8;"><strong>2 Park and gardens</strong></span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>1. Did you like going to parks as a child?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Yeah, definitely. I used to go to parks quite a lot when I was a kid, especially on weekends with my family. I mean, parks were probably one of the few places where I could run around freely, play games, and hang out with my friends. Looking back, those trips were actually a big part of my childhood.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>2. Do you still like going to parks now?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Yeah, I do, although I go there for different reasons now. These days, I usually visit parks when I need a break from studying or work because they’re much quieter and less stressful than crowded places. Sometimes I just take a walk, listen to music, or simply sit there to clear my mind.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>3. Would you like to see more parks in your city?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Absolutely. I think more parks would really improve people’s quality of life, especially in big cities where there’s a lot of traffic and pollution. Parks provide green spaces where people can exercise, relax, or spend time with their families. Plus, they make the city look much more livable and attractive.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>4. Are there any parks you want to go to in the future?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Hmm, yeah, definitely. I’d love to visit some famous national parks abroad, especially places with amazing scenery and wildlife. For example, I’ve always wanted to see places like Yellowstone or Banff because, you know, they look incredibly peaceful and breathtaking in photos and videos.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="ltr"><span style="font-size: 14pt; background-color: #fbeeb8;"><strong>3 Outer space and stars</strong></span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>1. Have you ever learnt about outer space and stars?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Yes, I have. I remember learning some basic things about the solar system and constellations in primary school. I was always fascinated by the universe, even though I didn’t go too deep into the science behind it.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>2. Do you like science fiction movies? Why?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Absolutely! I really enjoy sci-fi movies because they often explore the unknown, like time travel, aliens, or life on other planets. They spark my imagination and make me think about what might be possible in the future.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>3. Do you want to know more about outer space?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Yes, I do. I think space is full of mystery, and there’s still so much we don’t understand. I’d love to learn more about things like black holes, Mars exploration, or how astronauts live in space.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>4. Do you want to go into outer space in the future?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">To be honest, I think it would be an amazing experience, but I’m not sure I’m brave enough! The idea of floating in zero gravity sounds fun, but space travel also seems risky and uncomfortable. So maybe I’d just enjoy it through documentaries</p>
<hr>
<p dir="ltr"><span style="background-color: #fbeeb8; font-size: 14pt;"><strong>4 Building</strong></span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>1. Are there tall buildings near your home?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Yes, quite a few actually. I live in a fairly urbanized area, so the skyline is dotted with high-rise apartment blocks and commercial towers. One of the tallest buildings nearby is a modern office complex that really stands out because of its glass facade. It''s quite impressive, especially at night when it''s fully lit.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>2. Do you take photos of buildings?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Occasionally, yes. I’m particularly drawn to buildings with unique or historic architecture. When I travel, I often find myself photographing cathedrals, temples, or even old colonial structures—anything that has character or tells a story. It’s not just about aesthetics, but also capturing cultural heritage.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>3. Is there a building that you would like to visit?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Definitely! I’ve always wanted to visit the Sydney Opera House. Its design is so iconic and futuristic, and I think it would be fascinating to see it in person. Not just from the outside, but I’d love to attend a performance there too, to really soak in the atmosphere.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>4. Do you want to live in a tall building?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">To be honest, I wouldn’t mind it. Living on a high floor often comes with spectacular views and a quieter environment, away from the street noise. But at the same time, I’d be concerned about things like elevator breakdowns or feeling a bit isolated. So I guess it would depend on the design and location of the building.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="ltr"><span style="background-color: #fbeeb8; font-size: 14pt;"><strong>5 Gifts </strong></span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>1. What gift have you received recently?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Well, just a few weeks ago, one of my close friends gave me a book for my birthday — it was a novel I’d been wanting to read for a while. It wasn’t anything flashy, but it felt really thoughtful because she remembered what I liked. I was honestly touched by how personal it was.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>2. Have you ever sent handmade gifts to others?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Yes, actually. Back in high school, I made a scrapbook for my best friend’s birthday. It had photos, handwritten notes, and little drawings. It took quite a bit of time, but I really enjoyed the process. I think handmade gifts are special because they show genuine effort and creativity.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>3. Have you ever received a great gift?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Definitely. One of the most memorable gifts I got was a laptop from my parents when I got into university. It was both useful and meaningful because it marked a big milestone in my life. I still use it every day, and it reminds me of how supportive they are.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>4. What do you consider when choosing a gift?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">I usually think about the person’s personality and interests. For example, if someone enjoys cooking, I might get them a unique kitchen gadget. I also try to consider the occasion — like whether it’s a birthday, graduation, or just a small thank-you gift — because that can influence the style or price.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>5. Do you think you are good at choosing gifts?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">I’d say I’m pretty decent. I always try to be thoughtful and avoid generic things. I enjoy the process of finding something that will make the other person smile. Of course, it doesn’t always work out perfectly, but I think the effort really counts.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="ltr"><span style="font-size: 14pt; background-color: #fbeeb8;"><strong>6 Typing</strong></span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>1. Do you prefer typing or handwriting?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">To be honest, I prefer typing, especially when I need to write something long like an essay or a report. It’s much faster and more convenient, and I can easily edit my work without making a mess. But I still enjoy handwriting when it comes to jotting down quick notes or writing in a journal — it feels more personal.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>2. Do you type on a desktop or laptop keyboard every day?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Yes, I use my laptop keyboard almost every day. Whether I’m doing assignments, replying to emails, or even chatting with friends, typing is just part of my daily routine. I hardly ever use a desktop these days, since laptops are more portable.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>3. When did you learn how to type on a keyboard?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">I think I started learning in secondary school. At first, I typed pretty slowly with just two fingers, but over time I got faster. I never took a formal course — I just learned by doing, especially when I started using the internet more for school and entertainment.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>4. How do you improve your typing?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Well, I’ve improved mainly through practice. Typing regularly for schoolwork or messaging has made me faster over time. Occasionally, I use online typing tests to track my speed and accuracy. Also, using keyboard shortcuts helps me work more efficiently, especially when I’m multitasking.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="ltr"><span style="background-color: #fbeeb8; font-size: 14pt;"><strong>7 Pets and Animals</strong></span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>1. What''s your favourite animal? Why?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Well, I’d say my favourite animal is the elephant. I’ve always found them incredibly intelligent and gentle, despite their massive size. You know, they’re known for their strong memory and social bonds, which I think is really admirable. Also, in Vietnam, elephants are a symbol of strength and wisdom, especially in some cultural festivals.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>2. Where do you prefer to keep your pet, indoors or outdoors?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Hmm, I’d say it depends on the type of pet, but personally, I prefer keeping pets indoors. I feel it’s safer and more convenient, especially for animals like cats or small dogs. Plus, when pets stay inside, you get to interact with them more, which strengthens the bond. Of course, I make sure they have enough space and time outdoors too.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>3. Have you ever had a pet before?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Yes, actually, I had a dog when I was in primary school. His name was Lucky, and he was such a loyal companion. I used to walk him every evening, and he would always greet me excitedly when I got home. Having a pet definitely taught me responsibility from a young age.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>4. What is the most popular animal in your country?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Well, I think dogs are probably the most popular in Vietnam. Almost every neighborhood has families with dogs, either as pets or for guarding the house. Cats are quite common too, especially in rural areas where people keep them to catch mice. But overall, dogs are definitely more favored for their loyalty and companionship.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="ltr"><span style="font-size: 14pt; background-color: #fbeeb8;"><strong>8 Websites</strong></span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>1. What kinds of websites do you often visit?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">I often visit news websites, social media platforms, and entertainment sites. I like to stay updated on current events, so I check news websites daily. I also spend time on social media to connect with friends and family, and occasionally I visit streaming sites to watch movies or listen to music.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>2. What is your favourite website?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">My favorite website is probably YouTube. I love watching videos on a variety of topics, from educational content to travel vlogs and music. It’s a great source of entertainment and knowledge, and I appreciate the diversity of content available there.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>3. Are there any changes to the websites you often visit?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Yes, I’ve noticed some changes, especially with social media sites. They’re constantly updating their features and layouts to improve user experience. For example, many now include more video content and live streaming options, which weren’t as common a few years ago.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>4. What kinds of websites are popular in your country?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">In Vietnam, social media websites like Facebook, Zalo, and YouTube are very popular. News and entertainment sites are also widely visited, as well as e-commerce sites like Shopee and Lazada, which people use frequently for online shopping. These sites are popular because they make it easy for people to connect, stay informed, and shop conveniently.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="ltr"><strong><span style="font-size: 14pt; background-color: #fbeeb8;">9 Clothing</span></strong></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>1. What kind of clothes do you like to wear?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Well, I usually prefer simple and casual clothes, like T-shirts, jeans, or hoodies. I mean, comfort is probably the most important thing for me. But sometimes, if I’m going to a special event, I’ll dress a bit more formally.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>2. Do you prefer to wear comfortable and casual clothes or smart clothes?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">I’d definitely choose comfortable and casual clothes most of the time. They’re more practical for daily activities, and I feel more relaxed wearing them. That said, I still think smart clothes are important for formal occasions or professional settings.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>3. Do you like wearing T-shirts?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Yeah, absolutely. T-shirts are probably the clothing item I wear the most because they’re comfortable and easy to match with other clothes. Plus, they work well in hot weather, which is great where I live.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>4. Do you spend a lot of time choosing clothes?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Hmm, not really. I usually keep things simple, so I don’t spend too much time deciding what to wear. Unless it’s for an important occasion, I just pick something comfortable and suitable for the weather.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="ltr"><strong><span style="font-size: 14pt; background-color: #fbeeb8;">10 Science</span></strong></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>1. Do you like science?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Yeah, I do, to some extent. I mean, science helps us understand how the world works, which I find pretty fascinating. Although I’m not really into complicated theories, I still enjoy learning about topics related to space or technology.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>2. When did you start to learn about science?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Hmm, I think I started learning science in primary school. At first, it was just simple things like plants, animals, or basic experiments. But as I got older, the subjects became more detailed and interesting.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>3. Which science subject is interesting to you?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">I’d say astronomy is probably the most interesting one for me. I’ve always been curious about space, planets, and, you know, the possibility of life on other planets. I think it’s amazing how much scientists have discovered about the universe.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>4. What kinds of interesting things have you done with science?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Well, back in school, I remember doing some simple science experiments in class, like mixing chemicals or building small electric circuits. They were actually quite fun because we got to learn things in a more practical way instead of just reading textbooks.</p>
<p><strong id="docs-internal-guid-03169927-7fff-9ec4-dee5-cbdb0d0279db">5. Do you like watching science TV programs?</strong></p>
<p>Yeah, sometimes I do. I especially enjoy documentaries about space or new technology because they’re both educational and entertaining. Plus, I think visual programs make scientific topics much easier to understand.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="ltr"><span style="background-color: #f8cac6;"><strong><span style="font-size: 14pt; background-color: #f8cac6;">1 Describe a home that you like to visit but do not want to live in</span></strong></span></p>
<p dir="ltr">You should say:</p>
<p dir="ltr">Where it is</p>
<p dir="ltr">What it is like</p>
<p dir="ltr">Why you like to visit it</p>
<p dir="ltr">And explain why you would not like to live there </p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>Sample</strong>:</p>
<p dir="ltr">Well, I’d like to talk about my cousin’s house, which is a place I really enjoy visiting but probably wouldn’t want to live in permanently.</p>
<p dir="ltr">Her house is located in a small countryside area, about two hours away from my city. It’s a large traditional house with a beautiful garden, and the atmosphere there is really peaceful and relaxing. There are lots of trees, flowers, and open spaces around the house, so it feels very close to nature.</p>
<p dir="ltr">I like visiting it because it’s a perfect place to take a break from busy city life. Whenever I go there, I feel much calmer and less stressed. Usually, I spend time chatting with my cousin, eating home-cooked meals, or just sitting outside enjoying the fresh air. Honestly, it’s the kind of place where you can truly relax.</p>
<p dir="ltr">However, I don’t think I’d like to live there long-term. The main reason is that it’s quite far from the city center, so it’s not very convenient. There aren’t many shopping centers, entertainment places, or public services nearby. Also, I think I’d eventually get bored because the lifestyle there is much quieter and slower than what I’m used to.</p>
<p dir="ltr">So yeah, even though I really enjoy visiting that house occasionally, I still prefer living in a more modern and convenient area.</p>
<p dir="ltr"> </p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>Part 3:</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>1. Do people in your country like to visit others’ homes?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Yeah, definitely. In my country, visiting other people’s homes is quite common, especially during holidays, birthdays, or special occasions. I mean, it’s considered a good way to maintain relationships and spend time with family or friends.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>2. What do people do when they visit others?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Well, people usually chat, eat together, or sometimes bring small gifts like fruit or snacks. If it’s a special occasion, they might also celebrate or have a meal together. Honestly, visiting someone’s house is often more about socializing and enjoying each other’s company.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>3. What kind of place do people in your country like to live in?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">I think most people prefer living in places that are convenient and comfortable. For example, younger people often like modern apartments in the city because they’re close to work or entertainment areas, while older people may prefer quieter places with more space and greenery.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>4. What''s the difference between homes in cities and those in the countryside?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Hmm, there are quite a few differences. Homes in cities are usually smaller and more modern because space is limited and expensive. In contrast, countryside houses tend to be larger and surrounded by nature. Also, life in rural areas is generally quieter and less stressful than in big cities.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="ltr"><span style="background-color: #f8cac6;"><strong><span style="font-size: 14pt; background-color: #f8cac6;">2 Describe an occasion when many people were smiling</span></strong></span></p>
<p dir="ltr">You should say:</p>
<p dir="ltr">When it happened </p>
<p dir="ltr">Who you were with </p>
<p dir="ltr">What happened </p>
<p dir="ltr">And explain why most people were smiling</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>SAMPLE</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">One memorable occasion when I saw lots of people smiling was my birthday party last year, which turned out to be one of the happiest days I can remember.</p>
<p dir="ltr">It happened in early November, just a few weeks after I turned 18. Instead of a big party, I decided to have a small but meaningful gathering with my closest friends and family. We rented a rooftop space at a quiet café in the city, decorated it with fairy lights, and set up a little photo booth for fun.</p>
<p dir="ltr">I was with my parents, a few cousins, and around ten of my best friends. What made the evening so special — and full of smiles — was the surprise they had prepared for me. After we finished dinner, my friends played a short video montage they had secretly made, filled with childhood photos, funny clips, and heartfelt birthday messages. I was honestly speechless, and everyone in the room was either smiling or tearing up — in a good way.</p>
<p dir="ltr">I think the reason most people were smiling wasn’t just because it was a celebration, but because of the warmth and sincerity behind everything. There was a real sense of connection and joy in the air. We laughed a lot, took tons of silly pictures, and sang happy birthday louder than we probably should have.</p>
<p dir="ltr">Looking back, that evening reminded me how powerful small gestures can be. It wasn’t an expensive party or anything fancy, but the happiness was real — and contagious.</p>
<p dir="ltr"> </p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>PART 3</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>1. Do people smile more when they are younger or older?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Well, I think younger people tend to smile more because, you know, they’re usually more carefree and less stressed by responsibilities. Older people still smile, of course, but their smiles often come from deeper experiences rather than spontaneous joy. So both groups smile, but the reasons behind their smiles are quite different.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>2. Do you think people who like to smile are more friendly?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Generally, yes. Someone who smiles often usually appears more approachable and easy to talk to. But, to be fair, smiling doesn’t always mean a person is genuinely friendly — sometimes it’s just politeness or habit. Still, in most cases, people who smile more tend to create a warmer atmosphere around them.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>3. Why do most people smile in photographs?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Actually, smiling in photos has become a social norm. People want to look happy, confident, and presentable, especially when the picture might be shared online. And you know, a smile can make the moment look more positive than it really is. So it’s partly cultural and partly about creating a good impression</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>4. Do women smile more than men? Why?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Yes, in many cultures women do smile more. One reason is that women are often encouraged to appear gentle and friendly, while men may feel pressure to look serious or strong. But of course, it also depends on personality. Some men smile a lot, and some women don’t smile much at all.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>5. Why do most people smile in photographs?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">People smile because they want to capture a happy version of themselves. A smile makes the picture look more natural and lively. And, well, since photos often represent memories, people want those memories to look positive. So smiling has simply become the easiest way to express that.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="ltr"><span style="background-color: #f8cac6;"><strong><span style="font-size: 14pt; background-color: #f8cac6;">3 Describe a piece of technology (not a phone) that you would like to own</span></strong></span></p>
<p dir="ltr">You should say:</p>
<p dir="ltr">What it is</p>
<p dir="ltr">How much it costs</p>
<p dir="ltr">How you knew it</p>
<p dir="ltr">And explain why you would like to own it</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>SAMPLE</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Well, to be honest, I’m not usually the type to chase after every new release, but if there’s one device I’m currently dying to get my hands on, it’s definitely the latest iPad Pro.</p>
<p dir="ltr">As far as I know, it’s a high-end gadget, and it’s actually quite pricey. Depending on the storage and screen size, it can set you back anywhere from 800 to over 1,000 dollars, which is why I haven''t pulled the trigger just yet. I first stumbled across it while scrolling through some tech reviews on YouTube, and I was immediately blown away by its sleek design and that incredibly vibrant display.</p>
<p dir="ltr">The main reason I’d love to own one is for the productivity boost. I do a lot of creative work and note-taking, and the way the Apple Pencil works with the iPad Pro seems seamless. I mean, having a portable powerhouse that allows me to edit photos or design graphics on the go would be a total game-changer for my workflow. Plus, as someone who travels a lot, being able to leave my bulky laptop at home and just carry this lightweight device would be extremely convenient.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong> </strong></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>Part 3</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>1. What are the differences between the technology of the past and that of today?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">"Well, I’d say the biggest difference is the speed and connectivity. In the past, technology was quite clunky and mostly stand-alone, like a simple calculator or a basic desktop computer. But today, everything is integrated and incredibly fast. I mean, with the advent of the internet and cloud computing, we can access a vast amount of information in the blink of an eye. Technology today is much more portable and user-friendly compared to the bulky machines our parents used."</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>2. What technology do young people like to use?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">"I think it’s pretty obvious that smart devices are at the top of the list. Most young people are practically glued to their smartphones because they use them for everything—from social media to mobile gaming. Besides that, wearable tech like smartwatches and high-end tablets, such as the iPad Pro, are highly sought after. These gadgets allow them to stay connected and be productive on the go, which fits their fast-paced lifestyle perfectly."</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>3. What are the differences between online and face-to-face communication?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">"That’s an interesting one. I’d say the main difference is the non-verbal cues. When you speak face-to-face, you can see body language and hear the tone of voice, which makes it easier to avoid misunderstandings. Online communication, on the other hand, is much more convenient and instantaneous, but it can feel a bit impersonal. You know, it’s hard to build a deep emotional connection through just a screen or a text message."</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>4. Do you think technology has changed the way people communicate?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">"Oh, without a doubt. It has completely revolutionized how we interact with each other. In the past, if someone was far away, you had to write a letter and wait weeks for a reply. Now, we have instant messaging and video calls that bridge the geographical gap in seconds. However, while we are more connected than ever, I feel like the quality of our conversations has dropped a bit because people are often distracted by notifications."</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>5. What negative effects does technology have on people’s relationships?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">"Well, honestly, I think it can lead to a lot of social isolation. You often see couples or families sitting together at a restaurant, but everyone is staring at their own screens instead of talking. This lack of real interaction can create a sense of detachment over time. Also, social media can cause a lot of unnecessary jealousy or misunderstandings, which can strain a relationship if people aren''t careful about their digital habits."</p>
<hr>
<p dir="ltr"><strong><span style="font-size: 14pt; background-color: #f8cac6;">4 Describe a time when you gave advice to others</span></strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">You should say:</p>
<p dir="ltr">When it was</p>
<p dir="ltr">To whom you gave the advice</p>
<p dir="ltr">What the advice was</p>
<p dir="ltr">And explain why you gave the advice</p>
<p dir="ltr">Well, I remember a time about six months ago when I gave some advice to one of my classmates. She was preparing for the IELTS exam, and to be honest, she was really stressed out — especially about the Writing section. She kept telling me she had no idea how to organize her ideas or how to use academic vocabulary properly.</p>
<p dir="ltr">So yeah, during one of our study sessions, she asked me for some tips. I told her, you know, the first thing she should do is read model essays to understand the structure — like how to write clear topic sentences, use cohesive devices, and stay on topic. I also recommended that she keep a vocabulary journal to collect useful phrases and collocations. Actually, I shared some of my own writing samples with her and showed her how I planned my essays using outlines.</p>
<p dir="ltr">The reason I gave her this advice was because I had already taken the test and got a decent score, so I knew what worked for me. Plus, I just wanted to help her feel more confident and less overwhelmed. In the end, she followed the advice, and a few weeks later, she told me she scored 7.0 in Writing, which made me feel really proud and happy for her.</p>
<p dir="ltr"> </p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>Part 3</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>1. Should people prepare before giving advice?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">"Well, let me see... I’d say yes, definitely. Giving advice is actually a pretty big responsibility, so you shouldn''t just say the first thing that comes to mind, you know? It’s much better to think it over and really consider the other person''s situation first. I mean, if you''re too rushed, your advice might actually make things worse instead of helping them out."</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>2. Is it good to ask advice from strangers online?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">"To be honest, it’s a bit of a mixed bag. I mean, on one hand, you can get different points of view from people all over the world, which is great. But on the other hand, there’s so much fake information on the internet these days. So, I guess it’s fine for small things like tech tips, but for serious life decisions, you should be really careful about who you trust."</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>3. What are the personalities of people whose job is to give advice?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">"That’s an interesting question. I’d say they need two main traits. First of all, they must be great listeners—you can''t really help someone if you don''t understand them, right? And secondly, they should be open-minded. If they are too judgmental, people will just feel uncomfortable and won''t want to share their problems with them anymore."</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>4. What are the problems if you ask too many people for advice?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">"The biggest issue, I think, is that you just end up getting super confused. When you hear too many conflicting opinions, it becomes almost impossible to make a final choice. It’s like, you lose your own voice and end up feeling even more stressed than when you started. It’s basically a case of ''too many cooks in the kitchen''."</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>5. Why do some people think it is better to ask for advice from friends than from parents?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">"I think it mostly boils down to the fact that friends are closer to our age. They’re usually going through the same struggles, so their advice feels more relatable. With parents, you know, sometimes there’s a fear of being judged, or we might feel their advice is a bit old-fashioned and doesn''t quite fit today''s world."</p>
<hr>
<p dir="ltr"><span style="font-size: 14pt; background-color: #f8cac6;"><strong>5 Describe a food that people eat on special occasions/events</strong></span></p>
<p dir="ltr">You should say:</p>
<p dir="ltr">What it is</p>
<p dir="ltr">What the special event/occasion is</p>
<p dir="ltr">How it is cooked/made </p>
<p dir="ltr">And explain why people eat it on that special occasion/event </p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>Sample</strong>:</p>
<p dir="ltr">Well, I’d like to talk about Banh Chung, which is a very traditional Vietnamese dish that people usually eat during Tet Holiday, or Lunar New Year.</p>
<p dir="ltr">Banh Chung is made mainly from sticky rice, pork, and green beans. These ingredients are wrapped carefully in large green leaves to form a square shape, and then the cake is boiled for many hours, sometimes overnight. Honestly, making it takes a lot of time and effort, so families often prepare it together.</p>
<p dir="ltr">I think the reason why people eat Banh Chung during Tet is that it has a strong cultural meaning. In Vietnam, the cake symbolizes gratitude to ancestors and hopes for a prosperous new year. Also, because family members usually gather together to make and cook the cake, it helps create a warm and festive atmosphere.</p>
<p dir="ltr">Personally, I really enjoy this tradition because it’s not only about the food itself but also about spending quality time with family. I still remember staying up late with my relatives waiting for the cake to finish cooking and chatting together, which was honestly a really memorable experience.</p>
<p dir="ltr">So yeah, even though there are many modern foods nowadays, Banh Chung is still one of the most important traditional dishes during special occasions in Vietnam.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Part 3</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>1. Why are there special foods on special occasions or events?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Well, I think special foods are closely connected to culture and tradition. Certain dishes often symbolize good luck, happiness, or family reunion, so people prepare them during important celebrations. Also, special food helps create a festive atmosphere and makes the occasion feel more meaningful.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>2. What are the differences between everyday food and festival food?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">I think festival food is usually more special and time-consuming to prepare. It often includes expensive ingredients and traditional recipes that people don’t eat regularly. In contrast, everyday food is normally simpler, quicker to cook, and more practical for daily life.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>3. Are there any differences between the food people eat today and the food people ate in the past?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Yeah, definitely. Nowadays, people have access to a much wider variety of food because of globalization and modern technology. Fast food and international cuisine have become much more common. In the past, people mainly ate traditional homemade dishes, and their diets were usually simpler and healthier.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="ltr"><span style="font-size: 14pt; background-color: #f8cac6;"><strong>6 Describe an advertisement with a famous person in it</strong></span></p>
<p dir="ltr">You should say:</p>
<p dir="ltr">Who the person is</p>
<p dir="ltr">Where you can see it </p>
<p dir="ltr">What the advertisement is about</p>
<p dir="ltr">And explain how you feel about the advertisement </p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>Sanmple</strong>:</p>
<p dir="ltr">Well, I’d like to talk about an advertisement featuring a famous football player, Cristiano Ronaldo, which I saw quite a lot on YouTube and social media.</p>
<p dir="ltr">The advertisement was for a sports brand, and it mainly promoted sportswear and running shoes. In the video, Ronaldo was shown training hard, working out, and encouraging people to stay active and never give up on their goals.</p>
<p dir="ltr">I first saw this advertisement online a few months ago, and since Ronaldo is such a well-known athlete, it immediately caught my attention. I mean, even people who aren’t football fans probably know who he is.</p>
<p dir="ltr">Honestly, I really liked the advertisement because it felt inspiring and energetic rather than just trying to sell a product. The background music, visuals, and motivational message made it really memorable. Also, I think using a famous athlete was a smart idea because people tend to trust products more when they’re promoted by someone successful and influential.</p>
<p dir="ltr">Another reason I liked it is that it actually motivated me to exercise more and pay attention to my health. So yeah, compared to many other advertisements, this one left quite a strong impression on me.</p>
<p dir="ltr"> </p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>1. What are the advantages and disadvantages of advertisements?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr"> Well, advertisements have both positive and negative sides. On the positive side, they help people learn about new products, services, and special offers. They’re also important for businesses because they help increase sales. However, some advertisements can be misleading or too repetitive, which may annoy people and encourage unnecessary spending.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>2. Why are many advertisements endorsed by celebrities? How useful are they?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr"> I think companies use celebrities because famous people can attract attention very quickly. Fans often trust or admire celebrities, so they may be more willing to buy the products being promoted. Honestly, I think this strategy is quite effective, especially among young consumers.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>3. What is the most important factor in an advertisement?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr"> In my opinion, the most important factor is creativity. If an advertisement is interesting, memorable, or emotional, people are more likely to pay attention to it. At the same time, the message also needs to be clear and easy to understand.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>4. Why are some advertisements boring?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr"> Well, some ads are boring because they’re too repetitive or lack creativity. Sometimes companies focus too much on selling the product and forget to make the content entertaining or relatable. As a result, people may just skip the advertisement completely.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>5. Is advertising important for a company? Why?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Yes, definitely. Advertising is extremely important because it helps companies promote their products and build brand awareness. Without advertising, many businesses would struggle to attract customers, especially in highly competitive markets.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="ltr"><span style="background-color: #f8cac6;"><strong><span style="font-size: 14pt; background-color: #f8cac6;">7 Describe an ambition that you haven’t achieved</span></strong></span></p>
<p dir="ltr">You should say:</p>
<ul>
<li dir="ltr" aria-level="1">
<p dir="ltr" role="presentation">What it is</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr" aria-level="1">
<p dir="ltr" role="presentation">Why you haven’t achieved it</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr" aria-level="1">
<p dir="ltr" role="presentation">What you are doing about it now</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr" aria-level="1">
<p dir="ltr" role="presentation">And how you feel about it</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">One ambition I haven’t achieved yet is getting an IELTS Band 7. I’ve been studying for the IELTS exam for a while, but reaching that score has been challenging for me. I need Band 7 for my study plans, so it’s a goal I really want to accomplish.</p>
<p dir="ltr">The main reason I haven’t achieved it yet is because of certain areas that I find difficult, like speaking and writing. Even though I’ve gone over the rules and techniques, I still struggle with expressing myself clearly in writing, and sometimes I feel nervous during the speaking test, which holds me back from doing my best. There’s also the pressure to get everything right, which makes it harder to stay calm and focused.</p>
<p dir="ltr">To work toward this goal, I’m taking extra classes and practicing regularly. I’m going through sample tests and focusing on areas where I need improvement, like writing more complex sentences and speaking naturally. I also watch videos and listen to podcasts to pick up new vocabulary and expressions that can help me in both writing and speaking.</p>
<p dir="ltr">I feel determined to keep at it because I know how important this score is for my future. Although it’s tough, I’m confident that with consistent practice, I’ll get there. It’s a challenging goal, but I’m motivated to put in the effort and achieve it someday soo</p>
<p dir="ltr"> </p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>Part 3:</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>1. What ambitions do children usually have?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Children often dream of becoming doctors, astronauts, teachers, or athletes because they find these jobs exciting and inspiring. Many are influenced by movies, books, or role models and choose ambitions based on what they admire.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>2. Why are some people very ambitious in their work?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Some people are ambitious because they want success, financial stability, or personal growth. Others are naturally driven and competitive, always seeking higher positions and new challenges. Ambition is often influenced by upbringing and environment.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>3. Why don’t some people have dreams?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Some people lack dreams because they are content with their current life or lack motivation due to personal struggles. Others may have faced failures or discouragement, making them hesitant to set big goals. Sometimes, a lack of exposure to opportunities also limits ambition.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>4. How do people balance work and life?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">People balance work and life by setting clear priorities, managing time effectively, and making time for family and hobbies. Some practice work-life balance strategies like avoiding overtime, exercising regularly, or taking breaks to reduce stress.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="ltr"><span style="font-size: 14pt; background-color: #f8cac6;"><strong>8 Describe a difficult thing you did and succeeded </strong></span></p>
<p dir="ltr">You should say:</p>
<p dir="ltr">What it was</p>
<p dir="ltr">How you overcame the difficulties</p>
<p dir="ltr">Whether you got help</p>
<p dir="ltr">And explain how you felt after you succeeded</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Well, one of the most difficult things I’ve ever done was preparing for the IELTS Speaking test. Honestly, speaking English fluently and naturally wasn’t easy for me at all, especially at the beginning.</p>
<p dir="ltr">I started preparing seriously about six months ago, and I struggled a lot with pronunciation and confidence. I used to get really nervous whenever I had to speak in front of others, even in class. So yeah, that was a huge barrier for me.</p>
<p dir="ltr">To overcome this, I practiced every single day. I recorded myself answering sample questions, listened to native speakers on YouTube, and even joined an English-speaking club. I also asked one of my friends—who speaks English really well—to help correct my mistakes and give me feedback.</p>
<p dir="ltr">At first, it was frustrating because I didn’t see much progress. But over time, I got more comfortable and started speaking more fluently. Eventually, I took the real test, and I was so surprised—and happy—when I got a 7.5 in Speaking.</p>
<p dir="ltr">To be honest, I felt incredibly proud of myself. It wasn’t just about the score, but more about pushing myself to do something that I once thought was impossible. So yeah, it was tough, but the success made all the effort totally worth it.</p>
<p dir="ltr"> </p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>Part 3</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>1. Should people set goals for themselves?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Yeah, I think so. Setting goals gives people direction and motivation. Whether it’s something big like starting a business or small like exercising regularly, having a clear target helps you stay focused. Without goals, it’s easy to just drift through life without real progress.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>2. How would you define success?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Well, I guess success means different things to different people. For some, it’s about money or career achievements. But for others, it could be living a balanced life, being healthy, or having meaningful relationships. Personally, I think success is about reaching your own goals and feeling satisfied with your life.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>3. How can we judge whether young people are successful nowadays?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Hmm, it’s tricky. Some people look at academic results, job offers, or how much money they make. But I think we should also consider emotional well-being, personal growth, and whether they’re living a life that makes them happy. Success isn’t just about numbers—it’s about balance too.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>4. Are successful people often lonely?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">That’s an interesting question. In some cases, yes. People who focus too much on work or chasing success might sacrifice time with family and friends. But it doesn’t have to be that way. If someone has strong social support and manages their time well, they can be successful without feeling isolated.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="ltr"><strong><span style="font-size: 14pt; background-color: #f8cac6;">9 Describe a famous person you would like to meet</span></strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Who he/she is</p>
<p dir="ltr">How you knew him/her</p>
<p dir="ltr">How/where you would like to meet him/her</p>
<p dir="ltr">And explain why you would like to meet him/ her</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>SAMPLE</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">One famous person I’d really love to meet is Nguyễn Nhật Ánh, who is one of the most beloved writers in Vietnam. He’s best known for his coming-of-age novels that capture the beauty, innocence, and emotions of childhood and teenage life.</p>
<p dir="ltr">I first knew about him when I was in secondary school. My Vietnamese teacher gave us a copy of his book Kính Vạn Hoa, and I was completely drawn into the world he created. Since then, I’ve read many of his works like Mắt Biếc, Cho Tôi Xin Một Vé Đi Tuổi Thơ, and Tôi Thấy Hoa Vàng Trên Cỏ Xanh. His writing style is so simple yet poetic, and his stories always leave me with a sense of nostalgia.</p>
<p dir="ltr">If I had the chance, I’d love to meet him at a book signing event or maybe in a quiet coffee shop in Đà Lạt, where he’s said to find inspiration. I’d probably ask him how he’s able to write such relatable stories, and where he finds the emotional depth for his characters.</p>
<p dir="ltr">The reason I want to meet him is because his books have been a big part of my childhood. They taught me not only about friendship and love, but also about how to appreciate the small, beautiful things in life. He’s not just a writer to me—he’s someone who shaped the way I see the world.</p>
<p dir="ltr"> </p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>Part 3: </strong></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>1. What are the advantages and disadvantages of being a famous child?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">One clear advantage is that famous children get early access to unique opportunities, like working with professionals or earning money young.<br>However, they also face a lot of pressure, and often lose their privacy and freedom, which can lead to stress or even burnout.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>2. What can today’s children do to become famous?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">These days, children can become famous through social media platforms like TikTok or YouTube by sharing their talents or something funny and creative.<br>Some also gain popularity by joining TV talent shows or acting in movies, but going viral online is the most common way now.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>3. What can children do with their fame?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">If they’re guided well, children can use their fame to influence others positively—for example, by supporting charities or raising awareness about social issues.<br>Some may also use it to build a personal brand or even start a business, but they need help managing their image and finances.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>4. Do people become famous because of their talent?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Often, yes—people who are skilled in music, acting, or sports become famous because of real talent.But nowadays, some people gain fame just through viral videos or attention-grabbing content, so talent isn’t always the main factor anymore.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="ltr"><span style="font-size: 14pt; background-color: #f8cac6;"><strong>10 Describe a time you needed to use your imagination</strong></span></p>
<p dir="ltr">You should say:</p>
<p dir="ltr">When it was</p>
<p dir="ltr">Why you needed to use imagination</p>
<p dir="ltr">How difficult or easy it was</p>
<p dir="ltr">And explain how you felt about it</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>SAMPLE </strong></p>
<p dir="ltr"> Well, a memorable time when I had to use my imagination was about two years ago, when I was working on a group project at university. We had to design a creative marketing campaign for a small local coffee shop in Ho Chi Minh City, and our professor specifically asked us to come up with something original that could stand out from the competition.</p>
<p dir="ltr">We really needed to use our imagination because the shop didn’t have a big budget, so traditional advertising wasn’t an option. I remember spending hours brainstorming ideas, and eventually, I suggested creating a mini storytelling campaign. Basically, I imagined the coffee beans as “travelers” from different regions of Vietnam, such as Da Lat or Buon Ma Thuot, each with their own personality and backstory. The idea was to design short videos and posters showing their “journey” from the farm to the cup.</p>
<p dir="ltr">To be honest, it was quite challenging at first. I mean, turning coffee beans into characters isn’t something I had done before, so I had to push myself to think outside the box. But once the ideas started flowing, everything became easier and more enjoyable. My teammates also added their own creative touches, so the final concept turned out to be really interesting.</p>
<p dir="ltr">In the end, I felt incredibly proud and satisfied. Not only did our professor love the concept, but the owner of the coffee shop also decided to use part of our campaign for his social media page. It made me realise that using imagination can turn simple ideas into something unique and meaningful. That experience also boosted my confidence in creative thinking, which I believe is essential in many areas of life.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong> </strong></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>Part 3</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>1 Do you think adults can have lots of imagination?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Well, yes, definitely. Even though people often say imagination is stronger in children, I think adults can also be very imaginative. The difference is that adults tend to use their imagination in more practical ways, like solving work-related problems or planning for the future. Sometimes, stress or responsibilities limit their creativity, but when adults are in the right environment—like during brainstorming or artistic activities—they can actually be very imaginative.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>2 Do you think imagination is essential for scientists?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Oh absolutely. Imagination is one of the most important qualities for scientists because scientific breakthroughs always start with creative thinking. For example, imagining what life on other planets looks like or predicting future technologies requires a lot of imagination. Scientists need to think beyond what already exists and explore possibilities that people haven''t considered before. Without imagination, scientific progress would be much slower.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>3 What kinds of jobs need imagination?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Well, there are many jobs that rely heavily on imagination. Obvious ones include creative fields like design, filmmaking, advertising, and architecture. But even technical jobs such as engineering, software development, or scientific research require a strong sense of imagination to come up with innovative solutions. I’d say any job that involves problem-solving or creating something new needs imagination to some extent.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>4 What subjects are helpful for children’s imagination?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">I think subjects like art, literature, and music are especially helpful because they encourage children to express their ideas freely. Reading stories also allows them to picture different worlds and characters. Even science can stimulate imagination when children learn about space or animals. The key is giving children opportunities to explore and create, rather than just memorising information.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>5 What games help develop children’s imagination?</strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">Well, games that allow children to create their own stories or characters are great for developing imagination. For example, role-playing games, building blocks like LEGO, or even simple drawing games can help them think creatively. Outdoor games where kids pretend to be superheroes or explorers are also beneficial. In general, any game that encourages creativity and free thinking can boost a child’s imaginative ability.</p>', NULL, 'speaking', '2', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'https://cms.ieltspredictiontest.com/media/images/7-1780302009.png', 'published', true, 0, '[]', '{}', '2026-06-01 08:43:48.677+00', '2026-06-01 08:03:30.534038+00');
